snippet.textDisplay: Jeff, what is your recommendation for neck training/maintenance for a guy in his late 50's with reduced neck mobility and some radiculopathy (cervicothoracic syndrome)? snippet.textDisplay: Jeff you really nailed it on the Hurdle's stretch modification to incorporate more anterior rotation. This is key and people will be shocked how much farther they can reach. Another epic modification to this stretch is to bend the extended knee enough to clasp your hands under the arch of the foot. Those less flexible will find your forehead very close to your knee to start the stretch.  Then, using isometric tension in the biceps, pull on your foot and at the same time extending the leg.  Absolutely the most incredible hamstring stretch known to man.

snippet.textDisplay: Bridging the neck and head stands are the biggest reasons I quit my wrestling program in high school. Neck snapped I blacked out and quit breathing for almost 3 mins. I walked 2 miles home and didn't go back to practice the rest of the week. Next week we were doing the neck bridges the when it came to the dreaded head stands again I refuse and got harassed and kicked out... Never wrestled for the school again nor helped train others. Years ago I was doing the over head press, gorilla press they called it and I popped my neck again and woke up in sitting in the machine. Having a neck that pops between every vertebrae almost on command is horrible and those exercises shouldn't ever be forced upon anyone but a lot of wrestling and football programs utilized them??? Now if I pop or a chiropractor pops my top two vertebrae I'm left with a week long head ache and a metallic taste in my mouth???
